[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] The **circulation problem** and its variants are a generalisation of network flow problems, with the added constraint of a lower bound on edge flows, and with **flow conservation** also being required for the source and sink (i.e. there are no special nodes).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] In variants of the problem, there are multiple commodities flowing through the network, and a cost on the flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] (flow cannot appear or disappear in nodes).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] Finding a flow assignment satisfying the constraints gives a solution to the given circulation problem.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] There is also a lower bound on each flow of commodity.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] For the circulation problem, many polynomial algorithms have been developed (e.g., Edmonds–Karp algorithm, 1972; Tarjan 1987-1988).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] Tardos found the first strongly polynomial algorithm.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] For the case of multiple commodities, the problem is NP-complete for integer flows.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] For fractional flows, it is solvable in polynomial time, as one can formulate the problem as a linear program.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/circulation-problem] Below are given some problems, and how to solve them with the general circulation setup given above.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] In graph theory, a **flow network** (also known as a **transportation network**) is a directed graph where each edge has a **capacity** and each edge receives a flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] The amount of flow on an edge cannot exceed the capacity of the edge.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Often in operations research, a directed graph is called a **network**, the vertices are called **nodes** and the edges are called **arcs**.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] A flow must satisfy the restriction that the amount of flow into a node equals the amount of flow out of it, unless it is a **source**, which has only outgoing flow, or **sink**, which has only incoming flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] A flow network can be used to model traffic in a computer network, circulation with demands, fluids in pipes, currents in an electrical circuit, or anything similar in which something travels through a network of nodes.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] As such, efficient algorithms for solving network flows can also be applied to solve problems that can be reduced to a flow network, including survey design, airline scheduling, image segmentation, and the matching problem.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] A **network** is a directed graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) with a non-negative **capacity** function *c* for each edge, and without multiple arcs (i.e. edges with the same source and target nodes).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Without loss of generality, we may assume that if (*u*, *v*) ∈ *E*, then (*v*, *u*) is also a member of E.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] If two nodes in G are distinguished – one as the source s and the other as the sink t – then (*G*, *c*, *s*, *t*) is called a **flow network**.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] In flow networks, the source s is deficient, and the sink t is active.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Pseudo-flows, feasible flows, and pre-flows are all examples of flow functions.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] The **value** |*f*| of a feasible flow f for a network, is the net flow into the sink t of the flow network, that is: |*f*| = *x**f* (*t*).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Note, the flow value in a network is also equal to the total outgoing flow of source s, that is: |*f*| = −*x**f* (*s*).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Also, if we define *A* as a set of nodes in *G* such that *s* ∈ *A* and *t* ∉ *A*, the flow value is equal to the total net flow going out of A (i.e. |*f*| = *f* out(*A*) − *f* in(*A*)).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] The flow value in a network is the total amount of flow from s to t.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Flow decomposition is a process of breaking down a given flow into a collection of path flows and cycle flows.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Every flow through a network can be decomposed into one or more paths and corresponding quantities, such that each edge in the flow equals the sum of all quantities of paths that pass through it.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Flow decomposition is a powerful tool in optimization problems to maximize or minimize specific flow parameters.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] We do not use multiple arcs within a network because we can combine those arcs into a single arc.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Along with the other constraints, the skew symmetry constraint must be remembered during this step to maintain the direction of the original pseudo-flow arc.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Adding flow to an arc is the same as adding an arc with the capacity of zero.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] The **residual capacity** of an arc e with respect to a pseudo-flow f is denoted *c**f*, and it is the difference between the arc's capacity and its flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] From this we can construct a **residual network**, denoted *G**f* (*V*, *E**f*), with a capacity function *c**f* which models the amount of *available* capacity on the set of arcs in *G* = (*V*, *E*).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] More specifically, capacity function *c**f* of each arc (*u*, *v*) in the residual network represents the amount of flow which can be transferred from u to v given the current state of the flow within the network.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] This concept is used in Ford–Fulkerson algorithm which computes the maximum flow in a flow network.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Note that there can be an unsaturated path (a path with available capacity) from u to v in the residual network, even though there is no such path from u to v in the original network.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Since flows in opposite directions cancel out, *decreasing* the flow from v to u is the same as *increasing* the flow from u to v.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] More simply, an augmenting path is an available flow path from the source to the sink.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] A network is at maximum flow if and only if there is no augmenting path in the residual network *G**f*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] The **bottleneck** is the minimum residual capacity of all the edges in a given augmenting path.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] See example explained in the "Example" section of this article.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] The flow network is at maximum flow if and only if it has a bottleneck with a value equal to zero.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] If any augmenting path exists, its bottleneck weight will be greater than 0.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] In other words, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then there is an augmenting path from the source to the sink.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] However, we know that if there is any augmenting path, then the network is not at maximum flow, which in turn means that, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then the network is not at maximum flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] The term "augmenting the flow" for an augmenting path means updating the flow f of each arc in this augmenting path to equal the capacity *c* of the bottleneck.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Augmenting the flow corresponds to pushing additional flow along the augmenting path until there is no remaining available residual capacity in the bottleneck.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] Sometimes, when modeling a network with more than one source, a **supersource** is introduced to the graph.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] This consists of a vertex connected to each of the sources with edges of infinite capacity, so as to act as a global source.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] A similar construct for sinks is called a **supersink**.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] In Figure 1 you see a flow network with source labeled s, sink t, and four additional nodes.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/flow-network] The flow and capacity is denoted $f/c$ .
