[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] The algorithms of Sherman and Kelner, Lee, Orecchia and Sidford, respectively, find an approximately optimal maximum flow but only work in undirected graphs.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Orlin published a paper describing an $O(|V||E|)$ algorithm.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Liu, Richard Peng, Maximilian Probst Gutenberg, and Sushant Sachdeva published an almost-linear time algorithm running in $O(|E|^{1+o(1)})$ for the minimum-cost flow problem of which the maximum flow problem is a particular case.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] For the single-source shortest path (SSSP) problem with negative weights – another particular case of a minimum-cost flow problem – an algorithm running in almost-linear time has also been reported.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Both algorithms were deemed best papers at the 2022 Symposium on Foundations of Computer Science.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Note that several maximum flows may exist, and if arbitrary real (or even arbitrary rational) values of flow are permitted (instead of just integers), there is either exactly one maximum flow, or infinitely many, since there are infinitely many linear combinations of the base maximum flows.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In other words, if we send x units of flow on edge u in one maximum flow, and $y>x$ units of flow on u in another maximum flow, then for each $\Delta \in [0,y-x]$ we can send $x+\Delta$ units on u and route the flow on remaining edges accordingly, to obtain another maximum flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] If flow values can be any real or rational numbers, then there are infinitely many such $\Delta$ values for each pair $x,y$ .
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] The following tables show the historical development of algorithms for solving the maximum flow problem.
