[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In this expanded network, the vertex capacity constraint is removed and therefore the problem can be treated as the original maximum flow problem.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Given a directed graph $G=(V,E)$ and two vertices s and t , we are to find the maximum number of paths from s to t .
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] The paths must be independent, i.e., vertex-disjoint (except for s and t ).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] We can construct a network $N=(V,E)$ from G with vertex capacities, where the capacities of all vertices and all edges are 1 .
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Then the value of the maximum flow is equal to the maximum number of independent paths from s to t .
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In addition to the paths being edge-disjoint and/or vertex disjoint, the paths also have a length constraint: we count only paths whose length is exactly k , or at most k .
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Most variants of this problem are NP-complete, except for small values of k .
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] A **closure** of a directed graph is a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] The **closure problem** is the task of finding the maximum-weight or minimum-weight closure in a vertex-weighted directed graph.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In the baseball elimination problem there are *n* teams competing in a league.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] At a specific stage of the league season, *w**i* is the number of wins and *r**i* is the number of games left to play for team *i* and *r*ij is the number of games left against team *j*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] A team is eliminated if it has no chance to finish the season in the first place.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] The task of the baseball elimination problem is to determine which teams are eliminated at each point during the season.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Schwartz proposed a method which reduces this problem to maximum network flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In this method a network is created to determine whether team *k* is eliminated.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network with *s*,*t* ∈ *V* being the source and the sink respectively.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] One adds a game node*ij* – which represents the number of plays between these two teams.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] We also add a team node for each team and connect each game node {*i*, *j*} with *i* < *j* to *V*, and connects each of them from *s* by an edge with capacity *r**ij* – which represents the number of plays between these two teams.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] We also add a team node for each team and connect each game node {*i*, *j*} with two team nodes *i* and *j* to ensure one of them wins.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] One does not need to restrict the flow value on these edges.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Finally, edges are made from team node *i* to the sink node *t* and the capacity of *w**k* + *r**k* – *w**i* is set to prevent team *i* from winning more than *w**k* + *r**k*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In this method it is claimed team *k* is not eliminated if and only if a flow value of size *r*(*S* − {*k*}) exists in network *G*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In the mentioned article it is proved that this flow value is the maximum flow value from *s* to *t*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In the airline industry a major problem is the scheduling of the flight crews.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] The airline scheduling problem can be considered as an application of extended maximum network flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] The input of this problem is a set of flights *F* which contains the information about where and when each flight departs and arrives.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In one version of airline scheduling the goal is to produce a feasible schedule with at most *k* crews.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] To solve this problem one uses a variation of the circulation problem called bounded circulation which is the generalization of network flow problems, with the added constraint of a lower bound on edge flows.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network with *s*,*t* ∈ *V* as the source and the sink nodes.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] For the source and destination of every flight *i*, one adds two nodes to *V*, node *s**i* as the source and node *d**i* as the destination node of flight *i*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, 1] between each *d**i* and *t*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [1, 1] between each pair of *s**i* and *d**i*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, 1] between each *d**i* and *s**j*, if source *s**j* is reachable with a reasonable amount of time and cost from the destination of flight *i*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] An edge with capacity [0, ∞] between *s* and *t*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In the mentioned method, it is claimed and proved that finding a flow value of *k* in *G* between *s* and *t* is equal to finding a feasible schedule for flight set *F* with at most *k* crews.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Another version of airline scheduling is finding the minimum needed crews to perform all the flights.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] To find an answer to this problem, a bipartite graph *G'* = (*A* ∪ *B*, *E*) is created where each flight has a copy in set *A* and set *B*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] If the same plane can perform flight *j* after flight *i*, *i*∈*A* is connected to *j*∈*B*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] A matching in G' induces a schedule for *F* and obviously maximum bipartite matching in this graph produces an airline schedule with minimum number of crews.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] As it is mentioned in the Application part of this article, the maximum cardinality bipartite matching is an application of maximum flow problem.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] There are some factories that produce goods and some villages where the goods have to be delivered.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] They are connected by a networks of roads with each road having a capacity c for maximum goods that can flow through it.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] The problem is to find if there is a circulation that satisfies the demand.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] This problem can be transformed into a maximum-flow problem.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Add a sink node t and add edges from all villages vi to t with capacity di where di is the demand rate of village vi.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be this new network.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] If there exists a circulation, looking at the max-flow solution would give the answer as to how much goods have to be sent on a particular road for satisfying the demands.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] The problem can be extended by adding a lower bound on the flow on some edges.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] In their book, Kleinberg and Tardos present an algorithm for segmenting an image.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] They present an algorithm to find the background and the foreground in an image.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Indeed, for pixels in *A* (considered as the foreground), we gain *ai*; for all pixels in *B* (considered as the background), we gain *bi*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] On the border, between two adjacent pixels *i* and *j*, we loose *pij*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] We now construct the network whose nodes are the pixel, plus a source and a sink, see Figure on the right.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] We connect the source to pixel *i* by an edge of weight *ai*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] We connect the pixel *i* to the sink by an edge of weight *bi*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] We connect pixel *i* to pixel *j* with weight *pij*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] Now, it remains to compute a minimum cut in that network (or equivalently a maximum flow).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] With negative constraints, the problem becomes strongly NP-hard even for simple networks.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/maximum-flow-problem] With positive constraints, the problem is polynomial if fractional flows are allowed, but may be strongly NP-hard when the flows must be integral.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] In the mathematical discipline of graph theory, **Menger's theorem** says that in a finite graph, the size of a minimum cut set is equal to the maximum number of disjoint paths that can be found between any pair of vertices.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Proved by Karl Menger in 1927, it characterizes the connectivity of a graph.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] It is generalized by the max-flow min-cut theorem, which is a weighted, edge version, and which in turn is a special case of the strong duality theorem for linear programs.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] All these statements in both edge and vertex versions remain true in directed graphs (when considering directed paths).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Most direct proofs consider a more general statement to allow proving it by induction.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] It is also convenient to use definitions that include some degenerate cases.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] The following proof for undirected graphs works without change for directed graphs or multi-graphs, provided we take *path* to mean directed path.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] For sets of vertices *A,B ⊂ G* (not necessarily disjoint), an *AB-path* is a path in *G* with a starting vertex in *A*, a final vertex in *B*, and no internal vertices either in *A* or in *B*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] We allow a path with a single vertex in *A ∩ B* and zero edges.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] An *AB-separator* of size *k* is a set *S* of *k* vertices (which may intersect *A* and *B*) such that *G−S* contains no *AB*-path.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] An *AB-connector* of size *k* is a union of *k* vertex-disjoint *AB*-paths.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] In other words, if no *k*−1 vertices disconnect *A* from *B*, then there exist *k* disjoint paths from *A* to *B*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] This variant implies the above vertex-connectivity statement: for *x,y ∈ G* in the previous section, apply the current theorem to *G*−{*x,y*} with *A = N(x)*, *B = N(y)*, the neighboring vertices of *x,y*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Then a set of vertices disconnecting *x* and *y* is the same thing as an *AB*-separator, and removing the end vertices in a set of independent *xy*-paths gives an *AB*-connector.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] For *G* having an edge *e*, we may assume by induction that the Theorem holds for *G−e*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] If *G−e* has a minimal *AB*-separator of size *k*, then there is an *AB*-connector of size *k* in *G−e*, and hence in *G*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Otherwise, let *S* be a *AB*-separator of *G−e* of size less than *k*, so that every *AB*-path in *G* contains a vertex of *S* or the edge *e*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] The size of *S* must be *k-1*, since if it was less, *S* together with either endpoint of *e* would be a better *AB*-separator of *G*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] In *G−S* there is an *AB*-path through *e*, since *S* alone is too small to be an *AB*-separator of *G*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Let *v1* be the earlier and *v2* be the later vertex of *e* on such a path.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Then *v1* is reachable from *A* but not from *B* in *G−S−e*, while *v2* is reachable from *B* but not from *A*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Now, let *S1 = S ∪ {v1}*, and consider a minimum *AS1*-separator *T* in *G−e*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Since *v2* is not reachable from *A* in *G−S1*, *T* is also an *AS1*-separator in *G*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Then *T* is also an *AB*-separator in *G* (because every *AB*-path intersects *S1*).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] By induction, *G−e* contains an *AS1*-connector *C1* of size *k*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Because of its size, the endpoints of the paths in it must be exactly *S1*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Similarly, letting *S2 = S ∪ {v2}*, a minimum *S2B*-separator has size *k*, and there is an *S2B*-connector *C2* of size *k*, with paths whose starting points are exactly *S2*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Furthermore, since *S1* disconnects *G*, every path in *C1* is internally disjoint from every path in *C2*, and we can define an *AB*-connector of size *k* in *G* by concatenating paths (*k−1* paths through *S* and one path going through *e=v1v2*).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] The directed edge version of the theorem easily implies the other versions.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] To infer the directed graph vertex version, it suffices to split each vertex *v* into two vertices *v1*, *v2*, with all ingoing edges going to *v1*, all outgoing edges going from *v2*, and an additional edge from *v1* to *v2*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] The directed versions of the theorem immediately imply undirected versions: it suffices to replace each edge of an undirected graph with a pair of directed edges (a digon).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] The directed edge version in turn follows from its weighted variant, the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Its proofs are often correctness proofs for max flow algorithms.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] It is also a special case of the still more general (strong) duality theorem for linear programs.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] In this version the theorem follows in fairly easily from Kőnig's theorem: in a bipartite graph, the minimal size of a cover is equal to the maximal size of a matching.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] This is done as follows: replace every vertex *v* in the original digraph *D* by two vertices *v'*, *v''*, and every edge *uv* by the edge *u'v''*; additionally, include the edges *v'v''* for every vertex *v* that is neither in *A* nor *B*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] This results in a bipartite graph, whose one side consists of the vertices *v'*, and the other of the vertices *v''*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Applying Kőnig's theorem we obtain a matching *M* and a cover *C* of the same size.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] In particular, exactly one endpoint of each edge of *M* is in *C*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Add to *C* all vertices *a''*, for *a* in *A,* and all vertices *b'*, for *b* in *B*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Let *P* be the set of all *AB*-paths composed of edges *uv* in *D* such that *u'v''* belongs to M.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Let *Q* in the original graph consist of all vertices *v* such that both *v'* and *v''* belong to *C*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] It is straightforward to check that *Q* is an *AB*-separating set, that every path in the family *P* contains precisely one vertex from *Q*, and every vertex in *Q* lies on a path from *P*, as desired.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] Menger's theorem holds for infinite graphs, and in that context it applies to the minimum cut between any two elements that are either vertices or ends of the graph (Halin 1974).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] The following result of Ron Aharoni and Eli Berger was originally a conjecture proposed by Paul Erdős, and before being proved was known as the **Erdős–Menger conjecture**.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/menger-s-theorem] It is equivalent to Menger's theorem when the graph is finite.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In mathematical optimization, the **push–relabel algorithm** (alternatively, **preflow–push algorithm**) is an algorithm for computing maximum flows in a flow network.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The name "push–relabel" comes from the two basic operations used in the algorithm.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Throughout its execution, the algorithm maintains a "preflow" and gradually converts it into a maximum flow by moving flow locally between neighboring nodes using *push* operations under the guidance of an admissible network maintained by *relabel* operations.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In comparison, the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm performs global augmentations that send flow following paths from the source all the way to the sink.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push–relabel algorithm is considered one of the most efficient maximum flow algorithms.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The generic algorithm has a strongly polynomial *O*(*V* 2*E*) time complexity, which is asymptotically more efficient than the *O*(*VE* 2) Edmonds–Karp algorithm.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Specific variants of the algorithms achieve even lower time complexities.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The variant based on the highest label node selection rule has *O*(*V* 2√*E*) time complexity and is generally regarded as the benchmark for maximum flow algorithms.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Subcubic *O*(*VE*log(*V* 2/*E*)) time complexity can be achieved using dynamic trees, although in practice it is less efficient.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push–relabel algorithm has been extended to compute minimum cost flows.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The idea of distance labels has led to a more efficient augmenting path algorithm, which in turn can be incorporated back into the push–relabel algorithm to create a variant with even higher empirical performance.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A preflow is a flow in which the total amount flowing into a vertex may be greater than the total amount flowing out of it, allowing an algorithm to change the flow on a single arc.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This idea was originally conceived by Alexander V.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Karzanov and was published in 1974 in Soviet Mathematical Dokladi 15.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This pre-flow algorithm also used a push operation; however, it used distances in the auxiliary network to determine where to push the flow instead of a labeling system.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push-relabel algorithm was designed by Andrew V.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm was initially presented in November 1986 in STOC '86: Proceedings of the eighteenth annual ACM symposium on Theory of computing, and then officially in October 1988 as an article in the *Journal of the ACM*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Both papers detail a generic form of the algorithm terminating in *O*(*V* 2*E*) along with a *O*(*V* 3) sequential implementation, a *O*(*VE* log(*V* 2/*E*)) implementation using dynamic trees, and parallel/distributed implementation.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] As explained in, Goldberg–Tarjan introduced distance labels by incorporating them into the parallel maximum flow algorithm of Yossi Shiloach and Uzi Vishkin.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push–relabel algorithm uses a nonnegative integer valid **labeling function** which makes use of *distance labels*, or *heights*, on nodes to determine which arcs should be selected for the push operation.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This labeling function is denoted by 𝓁 : *V* → ℕ.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In the algorithm, the label values of s and t are fixed. 𝓁(*u*) is a lower bound of the unweighted distance from u to t in *G**f* if t is reachable from u.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If u has been disconnected from t, then 𝓁(*u*) − | *V* | is a lower bound of the unweighted distance from u to s.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] As a result, if a valid labeling function exists, there are no *s*-*t* paths in *G**f* because no such paths can be longer than | *V* | − 1.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The **admissible network** *G̃**f* (*V*, *Ẽ**f* ) is composed of the set of arcs *e* ∈ *E**f* that are admissible.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For a fixed flow *f*, a vertex *v ∉*{*s, t*} is called **active** if it has positive excess with respect to *f*, i.e., *x**f* (*u*) > 0.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm starts by creating a residual graph, initializing the preflow values to zero and performing a set of saturating push operations on residual arcs (*s*, *v*) exiting the source, where *v* ∈ *V* \ {*s*}.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Similarly, the labels are initialized such that the label at the source is the number of nodes in the graph, 𝓁(*s*) = | *V* |, and all other nodes are given a label of zero.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Once the initialization is complete the algorithm repeatedly performs either the push or relabel operations against active nodes until no applicable operation can be performed.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push operation applies on an admissible out-arc (*u*, *v*) of an active node u in *G**f*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A push operation that causes *f* (*u*, *v*) to reach *c*(*u*, *v*) is called a **saturating push** since it uses up all the available capacity of the residual arc.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Otherwise, all of the excess at the node is pushed across the residual arc.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This is called an **unsaturating** or **non-saturating push**.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The relabel operation applies on an active node u which is neither the source nor the sink without any admissible out-arcs in *Gf*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] It modifies 𝓁(*u*) to be the minimum value such that an admissible out-arc is created.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Note that this always increases 𝓁(*u*) and never creates a steep arc, which is an arc (*u*, *v*) such that *c**f* (*u*, *v*) > 0, and 𝓁(*u*) > 𝓁(*v*) + 1.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] After a push or relabel operation, 𝓁 remains a valid labeling function with respect to f.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For a push operation on an admissible arc (*u*, *v*), it may add an arc (*v*, *u*) to *Ef*, where 𝓁(*v*) = 𝓁(*u*) − 1 ≤ 𝓁(*u*) + 1; it may also remove the arc (*u*, *v*) from *E**f*, where it effectively removes the constraint 𝓁(*u*) ≤ 𝓁(*v*) + 1.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] To see that a relabel operation on node u preserves the validity of 𝓁(*u*), notice that this is trivially guaranteed by definition for the out-arcs of *u* in *G**f*.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For the in-arcs of u in *G**f*, the increased 𝓁(*u*) can only satisfy the constraints less tightly, not violate them.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The generic push–relabel algorithm is used as a proof of concept only and does not contain implementation details on how to select an active node for the push and relabel operations.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This generic version of the algorithm will terminate in *O*(*V*2*E*).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Since 𝓁(*s*) = | *V* |, 𝓁(*t*) = 0, and there are no paths longer than | *V* | − 1 in *G**f*, in order for 𝓁(*s*) to satisfy the valid labeling condition s must be disconnected from t.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] At initialisation, the algorithm fulfills this requirement by creating a pre-flow f that saturates all out-arcs of s, after which 𝓁(*v*) = 0 is trivially valid for all *v* ∈ *V* \ {*s*, *t*}.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] After initialisation, the algorithm repeatedly executes an applicable push or relabel operation until no such operations apply, at which point the pre-flow has been converted into a maximum flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm maintains the condition that 𝓁 is a valid labeling during its execution.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This can be proven true by examining the effects of the push and relabel operations on the label function 𝓁.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The relabel operation increases the label value by the associated minimum plus one which will always satisfy the 𝓁(*u*) ≤ 𝓁(*v*) + 1 constraint.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The push operation can send flow from u to v if 𝓁(*u*) = 𝓁(*v*) + 1.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The addition of (*v*, *u*) to *G**f* will not affect the valid labeling since 𝓁(*v*) = 𝓁(*u*) − 1.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The deletion of (*u*, *v*) from *G**f* removes the corresponding constraint since the valid labeling property 𝓁(*u*) ≤ 𝓁(*v*) + 1 only applies to residual arcs in *G**f* .
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If a preflow f and a valid labeling 𝓁 for f exists then there is no augmenting path from s to t in the residual graph *G**f* .
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This can be proven by contradiction based on inequalities which arise in the labeling function when supposing that an augmenting path does exist.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If the algorithm terminates, then all nodes in *V* \ {*s*, *t*} are not active.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This means all *v* ∈ *V* \ {*s*, *t*} have no excess flow, and with no excess the preflow f obeys the flow conservation constraint and can be considered a normal flow.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This flow is the maximum flow according to the max-flow min-cut theorem since there is no augmenting path from s to t.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Therefore, the algorithm will return the maximum flow upon termination.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In order to bound the time complexity of the algorithm, we must analyze the number of push and relabel operations which occur within the main loop.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The numbers of relabel, saturating push and nonsaturating push operations are analyzed separately.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In the algorithm, the relabel operation can be performed at most (2| *V* | − 1)(| *V* | − 2) < 2| *V* |2 times.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This is because the labeling 𝓁(*u*) value for any node *u* can never decrease, and the maximum label value is at most 2| *V* | − 1 for all nodes.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This means the relabel operation could potentially be performed 2| *V* | − 1 times for all nodes *V* \ {*s*, *t*} (i.e. | *V* | − 2).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This results in a bound of *O*(*V* 2) for the relabel operation.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Each saturating push on an admissible arc (*u*, *v*) removes the arc from *G**f* .
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For the arc to be reinserted into *G**f* for another saturating push, v must first be relabeled, followed by a push on the arc (*v*, *u*), then u must be relabeled.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In the process, 𝓁(*u*) increases by at least two.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Therefore, there are *O*(*V*) saturating pushes on (*u*, *v*), and the total number of saturating pushes is at most 2| *V* || *E* |.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This results in a time bound of *O*(*VE*) for the saturating push operations.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Bounding the number of nonsaturating pushes can be achieved via a potential argument.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] We use the potential function Φ = Σ[*u* ∈ *V* ∧ *x**f* (*u*) > 0] 𝓁(*u*) (i.e. Φ is the sum of the labels of all active nodes).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] It is obvious that Φ is 0 initially and stays nonnegative throughout the execution of the algorithm.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Both relabels and saturating pushes can increase Φ.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] However, the value of Φ must be equal to 0 at termination since there cannot be any remaining active nodes at the end of the algorithm's execution.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This means that over the execution of the algorithm, the nonsaturating pushes must make up the difference of the relabel and saturating push operations in order for Φ to terminate with a value of 0.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The relabel operation can increase Φ by at most (2| *V* | − 1)(| *V* | − 2).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A saturating push on (*u*, *v*) activates v if it was inactive before the push, increasing Φ by at most 2| *V* | − 1.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Hence, the total contribution of all saturating pushes operations to Φ is at most (2| *V* | − 1)(2| *V* || *E* |).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A nonsaturating push on (*u*, *v*) always deactivates u, but it can also activate v as in a saturating push.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] As a result, it decreases Φ by at least 𝓁(*u*) − 𝓁(*v*) = 1.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Since relabels and saturating pushes increase Φ, the total number of nonsaturating pushes must make up the difference of (2| *V* | − 1)(| *V* | − 2) + (2| *V* | − 1)(2| *V* || *E* |) ≤ 4| *V* |2| *E* |.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] This results in a time bound of *O*(*V* 2*E*) for the nonsaturating push operations.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In sum, the algorithm executes *O*(*V* 2) relabels, *O*(*VE*) saturating pushes and *O*(*V* 2*E*) nonsaturating pushes.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Data structures can be designed to pick and execute an applicable operation in *O*(1) time.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Therefore, the time complexity of the algorithm is *O*(*V* 2*E*).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The following is a sample execution of the generic push-relabel algorithm, as defined above, on the following simple network flow graph diagram.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] In the example, the *h* and *e* values denote the label 𝓁 and excess *x**f* , respectively, of the node during the execution of the algorithm.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Each residual graph in the example only contains the residual arcs with a capacity larger than zero.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Each residual graph may contain multiple iterations of the *perform operation* loop.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The example (but with initial flow of 0) can be run here interactively.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] While the generic push–relabel algorithm has *O*(*V* 2*E*) time complexity, efficient implementations achieve *O*(*V* 3) or lower time complexity by enforcing appropriate rules in selecting applicable push and relabel operations.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The empirical performance can be further improved by heuristics.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The "current-arc" data structure is a mechanism for visiting the in- and out-neighbors of a node in the flow network in a static circular order.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If a singly linked list of neighbors is created for a node, the data structure can be as simple as a pointer into the list that steps through the list and rewinds to the head when it runs off the end.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Based on the "current-arc" data structure, the discharge operation can be defined.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] A discharge operation applies on an active node and repeatedly pushes flow from the node until it becomes inactive, relabeling it as necessary to create admissible arcs in the process.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Finding the next admissible edge to push on has $O(1)$ amortized complexity.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The current-arc pointer only moves to the next neighbor when the edge to the current neighbor is saturated or non-admissible, and neither of these two properties can change until the active node u is relabelled.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Therefore, when the pointer runs off, there are no admissible unsaturated edges and we have to relabel the active node u , so having moved the pointer $O(V)$ times is paid for by the $O(V)$ relabel operation.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Definition of the discharge operation reduces the push–relabel algorithm to repeatedly selecting an active node to discharge.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Depending on the selection rule, the algorithm exhibits different time complexities.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] For the sake of brevity, we ignore s and t when referring to the nodes in the following discussion.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The FIFO push–relabel algorithm organizes the active nodes into a queue.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The initial active nodes can be inserted in arbitrary order.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm always removes the node at the front of the queue for discharging.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Whenever an inactive node becomes active, it is appended to the back of the queue.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm has *O*(*V* 3) time complexity.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The relabel-to-front push–relabel algorithm organizes all nodes into a linked list and maintains the invariant that the list is topologically sorted with respect to the admissible network.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm scans the list from front to back and performs a discharge operation on the current node if it is active.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If the node is relabeled, it is moved to the front of the list, and the scan is restarted from the front.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm also has *O*(*V* 3) time complexity.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The highest-label push–relabel algorithm organizes all nodes into buckets indexed by their labels.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm always selects an active node with the largest label to discharge.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm has $O(V^{2}{\sqrt {E}})$ time complexity.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If the lowest-label selection rule is used instead, the time complexity becomes *O*(*V* 2*E*).
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Although in the description of the generic push–relabel algorithm above, 𝓁(*u*) is set to zero for each node *u* other than s and t at the beginning, it is preferable to perform a backward breadth-first search from t to compute exact labels.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The algorithm is typically separated into two phases.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Phase one computes a maximum pre-flow by discharging only active nodes whose labels are below n.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Phase two converts the maximum preflow into a maximum flow by returning excess flow that cannot reach t to s.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] It can be shown that phase two has *O*(*VE*) time complexity regardless of the order of push and relabel operations and is therefore dominated by phase one.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Alternatively, it can be implemented using flow decomposition.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Heuristics are crucial to improving the empirical performance of the algorithm.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Two commonly used heuristics are the gap heuristic and the global relabeling heuristic.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The gap heuristic detects gaps in the labeling function.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] If there is a label 0 < 𝓁*'* < | *V* | for which there is no node u such that 𝓁(*u*) = 𝓁*'*, then any node u with 𝓁*'* < 𝓁(*u*) < | *V* | has been disconnected from t and can be relabeled to (| *V* | + 1) immediately.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] The global relabeling heuristic periodically performs backward breadth-first search from t in *G**f* to compute the exact labels of the nodes.
[src:push-relabel-maxflow/push-relabel-maximum-flow-algorithm] Both heuristics skip unhelpful relabel operations, which are a bottleneck of the algorithm and contribute to the ineffectiveness of dynamic trees.
